"Information risk is a critical component of your overall operational risks. It can be defined as the chance or possibility of harm being caused to a person or organisation as a result of a loss of the confidentiality, integrity or availability of information. This definition has stood up to inspection for many years and has been widely adopted. It can be applied to all types of information and all means of capturing, storing, handling or transmitting information, which makes it a highly useful definition. The adoption of basic good practice can dramatically reduce risk, but often these measures are not implemented. Only about 10% of business-critical systems that support leading organisations have adequate controls. By getting controls in good shape, organisations can substantially reduce information risk. Based on research, Marco Kapp and Simon Oxley of Citicus offer some best-practice advice."
